 Hits/effects of the training and visit extension system on farmers' 
 knowledge and adoption of technology: (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) from Pakistan 
 Syed Sajidin Hussain *,a,\ Derek Byerlee *Â·b, Paul W. Heisey c 
 a Farming-based 
 
 Money flow Research Unit, Tarnab, Peshawar, Pakistan 
 International Maize and Wheat Improvement Center (CIMMYT), 
 b Apdo. Postal6-641, Mexico City, D.F. 06600, Mexico, 
 c Liliongwe, Malawi 
 
 (Accepted 20 April1993) 
 
 Abstract 
 This paper provides (numbers-based) (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) on the hit/effect of the Training and Visit (T &amp; V) extension system in the 
 watered Punjab of Pakistan. Three models are carefully studied using limited (thing that changes (like a test score) because of something else that you control (like study time)) (moving backwards): the hit/effect of 
 T &amp; V on the number of extension contacts with farmers; the effect of extension contact on farmers' knowledge of 
 wheat technology; and the hit/effect ofT &amp; V on the adoption of improved wheat technology. The first model carefully studies 
 the hit/effect of T &amp; V on the amount of extension contact and the last thing just mentioned two models carefully study the effect on the amount. 
 and quality of extension contact. It is decided that T &amp; V has increased the amount but not the quality of 
 extension contact and this, in turn, has increased farmers' knowledge and adoption of technology. However, the 
 overall hits/effects have been small relative to those watched/followed in a almost the same  area in India. 
 
 Introduction 
 After a period in the 1960s and 1970s of (lowering in number/getting worse) interest in the role of extension in farming-based development, investment in extension systems increased very much in the 1980s. Much 
 of this increase was due to efforts by the World 
 Bank to redo extension systems using the 
 Training and Visit System (T &amp; V). The T &amp; V 
 system designed by Benor and others (1984) (fought for/pleaded for) a more controlled/punished and focused approach 
 * Corresponding authors. 
 Present address of Dr. Hussain: PATA Project, P.O. Box 14, 
 Mingora, Saidu Sharif, N.W.F.P., Pakistan. Tel. 536-5692. Fax 
 536-4259. 
 1 
 
 to extension through the following measures: (a) 
 removal of non-extension duties (e.g., supply of 
 inputs and collection of farming-based statistics) so 
 that village-level extension agents can focus on 
 information move (from one place to another); (b) increased extensionfarmer contact through a well-programmed 
 schedule of 2-weekly visits, often with 
 an increase in the ratio of extension workers to 
 farmers; (c) use of 'contact' farmers with close 
 links to extension and who are responsible for 
 passing extension messages to other farmers; (d) 
 increased training of village extension workers 
 through regularly managed and did/done courses; and (e) close 
 links between extension and research to secure/make sure of 
 the relevance of extension messages to farmers' 
 needs. 
 
