 Although the T &amp; V system has been done in over 40 countries, including the major 
 countries of Asia and Africa, there has been 
 surprisingly little difficult/strict/high quality test of its effectiveness. Some (not numbers-based) tests have questioned the approach ofT &amp; V as being 'top down' 
 and missing a means for organizing farmers to 
 express their own demands for extension guidance 
 (e.g., Axinn, 1988; Roling, 1988). Others have 
 noted problems in (putting into) use of T &amp; V, especially the choice of contact farmers (Moore, 
 1984), poor research-extension links (Chapman, 
 1988; Goodell, 1983), and weak linkages with 
 farmers at the field level (Dejene, 1989). In other 
 cases, the information content of extension messages given to contact farmers is not spread around 
 to close-by farmers in the area (Luhe, 1991). 
 A few studies have made a somewhat more 
 (numbers-based) test of the hits/effects of T &amp; V, 
 noting improvement in the number of extension 
 contacts (e.g., Dejene, 1989) and, sometimes, 
 increases in technology adoption and yields (Due 
 et al., 1987). However, none of these studies has 
 tried to separate the effects of extension from 
 the effects of other factors that may influence 
 extension contact and adoption, 1 or even to compare changes in technology adoption or working well with the situation that might have won 
 without (putting into) use of the T &amp; V 
 system. 
 Only one study has made a difficult/strict/high quality (numbers-based) analysis of the hits/effects of T &amp; V extension by 
 comparing the degree of farmer-extension contact and farmers' knowledge and working well in 
 two (next to) areas of northern India - one area 
 with 4 years of experience with the T &amp; V system, 
 and one area using the usual system of extension (Feder, Slade and Sundaram, 1986; Feder, 
 Lau and Slade, 1985; Feder and Slade, 1986; 
 from now on together referred to as F &amp;S). That 
 study decided that the T &amp; V system increased 
 extension contact and led to more fast diffusion 
 
 1 In fact, the usual approach has been to relate extension 
 contact to adoption or yields, without (thinking about/when one thinks about) the fact that 
 farmers with extension contacts are often not representative 
 farmers in terms of education, farm size, etc. 
 
 of knowledge in the area served by the T &amp; V 
 extension approach relative to the (next to) nonT &amp; V area. F &amp; S guessed an increase of at least 
 7% in wheat working well as a result of T &amp; V 
 extension. 
 The goal of this paper is to provide further (numbers-based) (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) of the hits/effects ofT &amp; V 
 extension from the Punjab of Pakistan in an watered cropping system in the after-Green Revolution phase of development. The setting is quite 
 almost the same  agroclimatically to the area studied by 
 F &amp; S in northern India and the cropping system 
 also focusses on wheat. Also, as in northern India, the T &amp; V extension approach was first introduced in the Pakistan Punjab in 1979. Early indications, however, suggest that T &amp; V extension 
 was not successful in increasing farmer contact, 
 adoption rates or yields in the Pakistan Punjab 
 (Khan et al. 1984). Data for the analysis of this paper provide a somewhat longer period for test of the hits/effects of T &amp; V. 
 
 2. Model and data sources 
 T &amp; V extension may affect both the amount 
 and quality of extension guidance, which in turn 
 affect farmers' technical knowledge and skills to 
 directly increase working well (through higher 
 technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) in using existing inputs) or to 
 indirectly increase working well (through changes 
 in input levels, (in other words), higher allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something)). 
 At the same time, the amount and quality of 
 extension guidance should not be seen as being 
 completely (coming from the outside of something); rather these (numbers that change/things that change) may 
 themselves be a function of farmers' (features/ qualities/ traits), especially education, farm size, (set of machines), etc., which decide/figure out demand for extension 
 guidance. Analysis of all these possible influences 
 on working well is a complex job. In this paper, 
 our data set enables an analysis of (a) (things that decide other things) of the amount of extension contact, (b) 
 (things that decide other things) of farmers' technical knowledge, 
 and (c) (things that decide other things) of the adoption of improved 
 technology being recommended by the extension 
 service. Unlike F &amp; S we are unable to test the 
 effects ofT &amp; V on working well, since the data set 
 employed was designed to measure the factors 
 
 S.S. Hussain et al. /Agricultural Money flow 10 (1994) 39-47 
 
 influencing the diffusion of new wheat technologies. However, in the farming systems under study, 
 adoption of new technologies and practices being 
 recommended by the extension service is carefully thought about/believed a necessary condition for increasing working well (Hussain, 1989). 2 
 A further major issue in measuring the hit/effect 
 of T &amp; V is to identify what would have happened 
 without T &amp; V. In this paper, we follow 
 the approach employed by F &amp;S of choosing touching, (compared to other things) (group of things that are all pretty much the same) areas in the same 
 agroclimatic zone, in which T &amp; V extension has 
 been practiced only in part of the area. This is 
 helped in the Pakistan Punjab, since T &amp; V 
 was introduced in only a few districts as a pilot 
 project. Because of this we examine the two major cropping systems in the Punjab - rice-wheat and 
 cotton-wheat. In each system, we have a random 
 sample of about 50 farmers in one district where 
 T &amp; V has been practiced for 6 years, and a random sample of about 100 farmers in (next to) 
 districts in the same cropping system in which 
 T &amp; V has not been practiced. We recognize that 
 this method assumes that (a) the close-by 
 districts are agroclimatically (group of things that are all pretty much the same), and 
 (b) the effects of T &amp; V do not 'spill over' into 
 close-by districts. Relating to/connected to the first 
 idea (you think is true), cropping system is a practical substitute 
 for agroclimatic zone; because of this areas with almost the same 
 cropping systems should also be agroclimatically 
 almost the same. Relating to/connected to the second idea (you think is true), 
 we, like F &amp;S, believe it is unlikely that significant 
 spillovers of extension information would happen 
 from one district to the next. 
 Overall we have a sample of 295 farmers, 101 
 of which are in T &amp; V districts. For each 
 farmer, described/explained data were collected for the 1986 
 crop season on extension contact, knowledge of 
 
 2 
 
 It would also be desirable to test the hits/effects of extension 
 
 for all major crops in the surveyed cropping systems. In the 
 surveyed area covered in this study, cotton, rice, maize and 
 sugar-cane are the other major crops. We have no reason to 
 expect the effects of extension on the other crops to be 
 greater than for wheat, especially since wheat is the major 
 winter crop and also a priority crop for research and extension, given its very important role in Pakistan's food security. 
 
 41 
 
 extension recommendations, technical knowledge 
 with respect to modern inputs (e.g., improved 
 varieties, (material that makes plants grow better)s and herbicides), and farmers' 
 adoption of these practices. Except for extension 
 contact, all the data relate to knowledge and use 
 of technology for wheat, a major crop covering 
 90% of cropped area in the winter season and a 
 crop grown by all farmers in the sample. The 
 selection of wheat as the focus of this study also 
 enables comparisons with F &amp; S, who studied 
 wheat technology and working well also. 
 From this data set we can specify a few models that guess the amount and quality of extension guidance and its hits/effects: 
 2.1. Amount of extension contact 
 Eq. (1) models (numbers that change/things that change) influencing extension 
 contact: 
 EXT= f(EDUC, AGE, FSIZE, ROAD, TANDY) 
 
 (1) 
 
 where EXT is a binary (number or thing that changes) (0, 1) for extension 
 contact in the year coming before the survey, EDUC 
 the number of years of formal education, AGE 
 farmer's age (years), FSIZE farm size (ha), ROAD 
 dummy (number or thing that changes) (0, 1) if village is on a sealed 
 road, and TANDY dummy (number or thing that changes) (0, 1) for a 
 T &amp; V district. This equation follows the standard 
 (detailed description of exactly what is required) that larger and more educated farmers will gain higher benefits from improved information (Feder and Slade, 1986) and that supply 
 of extension guidance will be easier or cost less for 
 farmers in (easy to get to, use, or understand) villages and for educated 
 farmers. We also guess that extension contact is more (existing all over a large area) in T &amp; V districts. This 
 equation then measures the effect of T &amp; V on 
 the amount of extension guidance. Since EXT is a 
 binary (number or thing that changes), this equation is guessed as a 
 logit model. 
 2.2. Effect of extension contact on knowledge of 
 recommended technology 
 Eq. (2) models (numbers that change/things that change) influencing farmers' 
 technical knowledge: 
 KNOWSCOR = f(EDUC, FSIZE, AGE, ROAD, RADIO, 
 TANDY,EXT,TANDY*EXT) 
 
 (2) 
 
 42 
 
 S.S. Hussain eta/./ Farming-based Money flow 10 (1994) 39-47 
 
 where KNowscoR represents an index of farmers' 
 knowledge of new wheat technology (defined below), and RADIO is a dummy (number or thing that changes) (0, 1) if the 
 farmer has listened to an extension-oriented program on the radio. This (number or thing that changes) represents an 
 different information source: the same radio 
 extension program is available in both T &amp; V and 
 non-T &amp; V areas. Other (numbers that change/things that change) are as defined 
 (before that/before now). 
 The extension (numbers that change/things that change) EXT, TANDY and 
 TANDY* EXT were included in two (detailed descriptions of exactly what is required): 
 - TANDY included alone measures possible effects of T &amp; V on both the amount and quality 
 of extension guidance for all farmers in T &amp; V 
 districts relative to farmers in non-T &amp; V districts. 
 - EXT and TANDY* EXT measure the effects of 
 the amount and quality of extension guidance, 
 (match up each pair of items in order). TANDY* EXT tests whether farmers 
 in T &amp; V areas who have extension contact 
 receive higher quality extension guidance than 
 farmers in non-T &amp; V districts. 
 Note that in this equation the (thing that changes (like a test score) because of something else that you control (like study time)) 
 lies in a bounded range (e.g., zero to a specific 
 number depending upon the highest knowledge score); this way a two-tailed Tobit moving backward is 
 applied. 
 2.3. Adoption of recommended technology 
 
 Finally, Eq. (3) models (numbers that change/things that change) influencing 
 technology adoption. 
 ADOPTi =f(EDUC, FSIZE, AGE, ROAD, RADIO, 
 TANDY,EXT,TANDY*EXT) 
 (3) 
 where ADOPTi is a (number or thing that changes) measuring adoption/ 
 non-adoption of improved practice i or the level 
 of improved practice i, and other (numbers that change/things that change) are as 
 (before that/before now) specified. 
 The analysis thinks about/believes the adoption of three 
 practices widely (helped increase/showed in a good way) by extension - new 
 wheat varieties, use of phosphorus, and chemical 
 weed control. Although farmers in the study areas have had 15-20 years of experience with 
 modern wheat varieties introduced with the 
 Green Revolution, the disease resistance of these 
 varieties can break down over time, and research 
 and extension were (helping increase/showing in a good way) newer disease-resistant varieties released in the previous 5 years 
 to replace the older varieties. Also, farmers 
 
 have (large/relatively large) experience with using nitrogenous (material that makes plants grow better)s, but adoption of phosphatic (material that makes plants grow better)s began only after about 1975. Most farmers 
 now use phosphatic (material that makes plants grow better)s, and the analysis of 
 adoption provides (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) on the effects of extension in the later stages of adoption of a practice. Finally, weeds have become a major factor 
 limiting wheat yields, and both extension and the 
 (people and businesses that are not part of the government) are (helping increase/showing in a good way) use of chemical weed 
 control. However, adoption of herbicides is in the 
 early stages, with only about 10% of surveyed 
 farmers using herbicides. Because of this we carefully study 
 adoption in three different situations - replacement of an already adopted practice with a 
 newer practice (variety), the later stages of adoption of a new practice (phosphatic (material that makes plants grow better)), and 
 the early stages of adoption of a new practice 
 (herbicide). 
 To represent adoption of these practices, 
 ADOPT may be a binary (number or thing that changes) (0, 1) (e.g., for 
 use of a new variety) in which case a logit model 
 is employed, or it may lie in a bounded range 
 (e.g., zero to any level of phosphorus use) in 
 which case a Tobit model is most appropriate. 
 The above (detailed descriptions of exactly what is required) for Eqs. (1)-(3) suggest 
 partially recursive models. Certain (numbers that change/things that change) (e.g., 
 EDUC and TANDY) are assumed to affect extension 
 contact (ExT), and EXT in combination with other 
 factors is assumed to affect farmers' knowledge 
 (KNowscoR) and adoption (ADOPT). The ideas (you think are true) of Least Squares guess are obviously 
 appropriate for Eq. (1). However, some (detailed description of exactly what is required) bias might be expected by guessing Eqs. (2) 
 and (3) in the present form without any restrictions on the covariance matrix (Judge et al., 1982). 
 This way the effect of extension on knowledge and 
 adoption might be underestimated. 
 3. Scientific results 
 
 Before presenting results of the guessed 
 models, it is worth noting some background information on the area analysed. The survey area 
 covering the major cropping systems of the Punjab is mainly watered by narrow waterway and is carefully thought about/believed 
 to be one of the most productive areas of 
 Pakistan. Wheat is the major winter crop and is 
 grown under two cropping systems: rice-wheat 
 
