 and cotton-wheat. Even after 6 years of T &amp; V 
 extension, the amount of extension contact was 
 still low in the T &amp; V districts. Only 43% and 24% 
 of farmers in the T &amp; V districts in each cropping 
 system had had any contact with extension in the 
 year before the survey. Very differently, Feder, Slade 
 and Sundaram (1986) found 65% of farmers in 
 T &amp; V areas of northern India had had contact 
 with extension in the month before the survey. 
 Also, the level of farmers' technical knowledge in the Pakistan Punjab is (compared to other things) low. 
 Only half of farmers in T &amp; V districts had any 
 knowledge of new varieties or could distinguish 
 (material that makes plants grow better) (vitamins, minerals, protein, etc.); less than 7% could name a 
 recommended herbicide. Finally, only 41% and 
 9% of farmers in T &amp; V districts had adopted 
 newer wheat varieties and herbicides, (match up each pair of items in order). Most farmers (80%) had adopted phosphatic (material that makes plants grow better)s but at less than half of the 
 recommended dose. These levels of knowledge 
 and adoption are much lower than similar figures for India reported by F &amp; S. 
 Moving backward results of the guessed models for 
 the amount and quality of extension guidance and 
 its hit/effect are presented below. We at first ran 
 all (moving backwards) separately for each cropping sys- 
 
 tern. There were some differences in results between the two cropping systems, but the major 
 ends/end results presented below hold for both cropping systems, which for simpleness of presentation 
 are combined in the following analysis. 
 Because there are no standard goodness of fit 
 tests for Logit, Probit and Tobit models, we figure out/calculate  chi-squared statistics to test the combined effects 
 of the (things that you control (like study times), that cause other things to change (like test scores)). The chi-squared 
 values for most of the models are highly significant. 
 
