 (meaningful numbers) hit/effect on farmers' technical knowledge (KNOWTECH) but had no significant 
 hit/effect on farmers' knowledge of recommendations (KNOWREc). These results suggest that extension has more of an educational role. The fact 
 that the coefficients for TANDY * EXT were in 
 both cases negative adds support to the idea that 
 T &amp; V has not improved the quality of extension 
 guidance; rather the effects of T &amp; V are the result 
 only of increased amount of extension contact. 
 The most important factor in increasing farmers' knowledge (both knowledge of recommendations and technical knowledge) was the educational level of farmers. The coefficient for education (EDuc) is positive and (related to numbers) highly significant in all models, supporting (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) from 
 other studies that formal education plays an important role in increasing farmers' knowledge 
 about new farming-based technologies (Lockheed et 
 al., 1980). 
 
 3.3. Adoption of recommended technology 
 Finally, we examined factors affecting the 
 adoption of the three (related to computers and science) parts/pieces 
 being (helped increase/showed in a good way) by extension. Results of the guessed Logit and Tobit models are presented in 
 Table 2. Overall extension contact (measured by 
 EXT) has a significant effect on adoption of chemical weed control, but not on use of new varieties 
 or phosphorus (material that makes plants grow better). T &amp; V extension may 
 have some effect on the overall adoption of 
 chemical weed control as shown by the positive 
 coefficient for TANDY in model 1 (significant at 
 the 10% level); in contrast the effects of T &amp; V for 
 new varieties and phosphorus use tends to be 
 negative. Chemical weed control is the newest 
 technology and is still at an early stage of adoption, and this may explain the importance of 
 extension contact in the adoption of this technology. However, as in the case of the effects of 
 
 46 
 
 S.S. Hussain et al. /Agricultural Money flow 10 (1994) 39-47 
 
 extension on knowledge score there is no (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) that the T &amp; V system increases the quality 
 of extension guidance. 
 Other important ((related to numbers) significant) (numbers that change/things that change) affecting adoption are education, farm size 
 and age of the person who responded. Education improves/increases adoption of improved varieties and 
 herbicides, again focusing on the role of formal 
 education in using new technology. Also, farm 
 size has an overall good effect on the adoption of new technology, especially new varieties, 
 possibly reflecting the greater ability of larger 
 farmers to experiment with new ways of doing things. However, extension radio programs have no effect on 
 adoption, (even though there is the existence of) their seen/obvious positive effect 
 on farmers' knowledge. As expected, none of 
 these (numbers that change/things that change) influences adoption of phosphatic 
 (material that makes plants grow better), which is in the late stage of adoption. 
 
 4. Why is T&amp;V less effective in Pakistan? 
 
 The results suggest that although T &amp; V extension has increased the amount of extension guidance, it has not been very effective relative to 
 traditional extension in increasing farmers' technical knowledge or the rate of adoption of new 
 technology - that is, the quality of extension 
 guidance has not improved with introduction of 
 T &amp; V. These results contrast with those of F &amp; S 
 in a similar area of India. We guess 
 that there are two major reasons for the seen/obvious 
 lack of hit/effect of T &amp; V on extension quality in 
 Pakistan. First, there were problems of starting the T &amp; V system as planned. For example, Khan et al. (1984) found that 20% of the 
 contact farmers in the T &amp; V area did not even 
 recognize that they were in fact contact farmers 
 and so the information flow of extension messages often stopped at the contact farmer. Also, 
 communication between research and extension 
 in the T &amp; V target area is weak. The (not being there; not being present) of a 
 research-extension coordinator may be one reason for this lack of planned linkage, as noted in 
 other T &amp; V projects (Dejene, 1989). 
 Second, because an effective (able to change and get better) research 
 program is missing extension, messages are often 
 inappropriate to farmers' facts or conditions (that surround someone). Adap- 
 
 tive research in the area is usually targeted for 
 clearly stated/particular valuable things and doesn't have a farming systems 
 (way of seeing things / sensible view of what is and is not important). Recommendations developed by 
 (able to change and get better) research are usually not locationspecific. Rather, they are made for a wide area 
 without taking into account the (large/relatively large) (quality of changing over time or at different places) in the (related to how much money and power people have) and agro-(related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) 
 facts or conditions that surround farmers in what appears at first 
 to be a (compared to other things) (group of things that are all pretty much the same) watered (surrounding conditions). For example, wheat produces /gives up are low in part 
 because of an increasing habit/desire to plant wheat 
 late in both the rice-wheat and cotton-wheat 
 cropping systems due to late collecting of the 
 previous crop. Although it is (money-based)/cheaply clear to trade-off wheat yields in this way, recommendations for (material that makes plants grow better) use and crop-watering/rinsing with water are 
 made assuming that the crop is planted on time 
 (Byerlee, Akhter and Hobbs, 1987). Because of this a much 
 stronger program of (able to change and get better) research put into use with a farming systems (way of seeing things / sensible view of what is and is not important) and 
 closely linked to extension is needed in order to 
 develop more appropriate extension messages .. 
 
 5. Ends/end results 
 Although the T &amp; V extension system has been 
 widely (helped increase/showed in a good way) in many countries, it has been 
 subject to little difficult/strict/high quality test. The results 
 presented in this paper for the Pakistan Punjab 
 point to/show that T &amp; V, after 7 years of experience, 
 had had less impact than people thought on farmers' 
 technical knowledge or on adoption of improved 
 practices. The T &amp; V system does seem to have 
 increased the amount of extension contact, probably because the ratio of extension agents to 
 farmers has been increased in the T &amp; V districts 
 carefully studied. Those farmers who have more extension contact do tend to have better technical 
 knowledge and have also adopted chemical weed 
 control earlier. However, T &amp; V has not had any 
 effect on the quality of extension contact. Since a 
 major goal of the T &amp; V system is to increase 
 the quality of extension guidance and to make extension messages more widely known through the 
 contact-farmer approach, our results do not support the ends/end results of Feder and Slade (1986) on 
 
 S.S. Hussain et al. /Agricultural Money flow 10 (1994) 39-47 
 
 the positive effects of T &amp; V in a almost the same  watered 
 area in India. 7 In our experience, the limited 
 success of T &amp; V in Pakistan reflects problems of 
 putting into use (for example, a small proportion 
 of farmers had contact with extension, relative to 
 India), as well as lack of (able to change and get better) research to 
 make recommendations more related to farmers. 
 (even though there is the existence of) the seen/obvious lack of hit/effect of T &amp; V 
 extension watched/followed in this study, the analysis does 
 provide interesting results on the effects of other 
 (numbers that change/things that change) on farmers' extension contact, technical 
 knowledge and adoption. Education and farm 
 size are more important (numbers that change/things that change) than T &amp; V in 
 influencing extension contact, underlining the 
 well-known bias of extension toward improveducated and richer farmers. Farmers' educational level, measured in terms of years of formal 
 education, also has a regularly large and significant effect on farmers' technical knowledge and 
 adoption. Radio programs also appear to be partly 
 effective as an extension device. Other (numbers that change/things that change) 
 such as age and access to a good road do not 
 appear directly to affect farmers' technical knowledge and adoption, once differences in education 
 and extension contact have been taken into account. These results reinforce the importance of 
 investment in formal education in increasing working well in after-Green Revolution farming 
 (Lockheed et al. 1980; Phillips, 1987). 
 
